14. Delete All Occurrences in Doubly Linked List

📌 Problem Statement  
Given the head of a doubly linked list and a target value, delete all nodes that have the given target value and return the updated head.

/*
Definition of doubly linked list:
struct ListNode
{
    int val;
    ListNode *next;
    ListNode *prev;
    ListNode()
    {
        val = 0;
        next = NULL;
        prev = NULL;
    }
    ListNode(int data1)
    {
        val = data1;
        next = NULL;
        prev = NULL;
    }
    ListNode(int data1, ListNode *next1, ListNode *prev1)
    {
        val = data1;
        next = next1;
        prev = prev1;
    }
};
*/

class Solution {
public:
    ListNode * deleteAllOccurrences(ListNode* head, int target) {
        ListNode* temp = head;
        while(temp != NULL){
            if(temp->val == target){
                if(temp == head){
                    head = temp->next;
                }
                ListNode* prevNode = temp->prev;
                ListNode* nextNode = temp->next;

                if(prevNode) prevNode->next = nextNode;
                if(nextNode) nextNode->prev = prevNode;

                free(temp);
                temp = nextNode;
            }else{
                temp = temp->next;
            }
        }
        return head;
    }
};

---

🧠 Approach  
This solution traverses the doubly linked list and removes nodes matching the target value by updating previous and next pointers.

Steps:
1. Traverse the list using a temporary pointer  
2. If the current node value matches the target:
   - Update the head if needed  
   - Adjust previous and next node links  
3. Move to the next node after deletion  
4. Continue until the entire list is processed  

---

⚙️ Implementation Details  
- Use a temp pointer to traverse the list  
- If node to be deleted is the head, update head  
- Store previous and next nodes before deletion  
- Update:
  - prevNode->next = nextNode  
  - nextNode->prev = prevNode  
- Free the current node and move ahead safely  

---

⏱ Time Complexity  
O(N)

💾 Space Complexity  
O(1)

---

🎯 Key Concepts  
- Doubly linked list traversal  
- Pointer updates (prev and next)  
- Safe node deletion  

---

✅ Outcome  
Efficiently removes all occurrences of the target value while maintaining the structure of the doubly linked list.





15. Find Pairs with Given Sum in Doubly Linked List

📌 Problem Statement  
Given the head of a sorted doubly linked list and a target value, find all pairs of nodes whose sum is equal to the target. Return the pairs as a list of values.

/*
class ListNode {
public:
    int val;
    ListNode* next;
    ListNode* prev; 

    ListNode(int value) : val(value), next(nullptr), prev(nullptr) {}

    ~ListNode() {
        delete next;
    }
};
*/

class Solution {
public:
ListNode* findTail(ListNode* head){
    ListNode* tail = head;
    while(tail->next != NULL) tail = tail->next;

    return tail;
}
    vector<vector<int>> findPairsWithGivenSum(ListNode* head, int target) {
        vector<vector<int>> ans;
        ListNode* left = head;
        ListNode* right = findTail(head);

        while(left->val < right->val){
            if(left->val + right->val == target){
                ans.push_back({left->val , right->val});
                left = left->next;
                right = right->prev;
            }else if(left->val + right->val < target){
                left = left->next;
            }else{
                right = right->prev;
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};

---

🧠 Approach  
This solution uses the two-pointer technique on a doubly linked list.

Steps:
1. Initialize two pointers:
   - left pointer at the head  
   - right pointer at the tail  

2. Traverse the list:
   - If sum equals target, store the pair and move both pointers  
   - If sum is less than target, move left pointer forward  
   - If sum is greater than target, move right pointer backward  

3. Continue until pointers meet  

---

⚙️ Implementation Details  
- Use a helper function to find the tail of the list  
- left starts from head  
- right starts from tail  
- Use prev and next pointers to move backward and forward  
- Store valid pairs in a 2D vector  

---

⏱ Time Complexity  
O(N)

💾 Space Complexity  
O(K) (for storing pairs)

---

🎯 Key Concepts  
- Two-pointer technique  
- Doubly linked list traversal  
- Efficient pair finding in sorted structure  

---

✅ Outcome  
Efficiently finds all pairs with the given sum in a single traversal using the two-pointer approach.





